				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Fun and learning are a great combination. You get to enjoy yourself now, and take some knowledge with you into the future. With that in mind, here&#8217;s another website recommendation. As part of the <a title="讀賣新聞　ネット＆デジタル" href="http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/net/">Yomiuri Shimbun Online Geek　Section</a>, there&#8217;s a fun column called &#8220;<a target="_blank" title="モニ太のデジタル辞典" href="http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/net/column/yougo/">Monita&#8217;s Digital Dictionary</a>&#8220;, it isn&#8217;t really a dictionary at all, but a place where a dog (yes, a dog) has articles that discuss, expound on and define everything from what a device driver is to the latest cool words being used online in general and by Japanese internet nerds in particular. It&#8217;s a lot of fun, and there&#8217;s always a humorous little comic that goes with it. Without gushing, this really is an inspiringly lucid example of technical writing or at least writing on a technical subject.The author, <a target="_blank" title="唐沢なをきオフィシャルウェブサイト" href="http://www.nawosan.com/">KARASAWA Nawoki, also maintains his own site</a>. Tell him Khatzumoto sent you.</p>
